        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>BKbrgh</placeName>
                    <date>12/8/78<ref target="#foot.f1"/></date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I thank you very much for your kind letter.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I regret extremely not to have found you at home &amp; hope to be more fortunate another time.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> If ever you should come on the continent, I should be most thankful to you to let me know it, so that I might try to have the honour of making your personal acquaintance.</p>
                    <p>Allow me to profit by this letter to congratulate you very sincerely on your recent election as an Associate of the French Acad. of Sc<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I remain, Dear Sir | Yours most respectfully</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The place and date were added to the draft in a contemporary hand, probably Errera’s; the rest of the draft is not in his handwriting.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="./DCP-LETT-11644.xml">Letter to Leo Errera, 8 August [1878]</ref>. The surviving envelope indicates that CD’s letter was posted to London, but forwarded to Blankenberghe (now Blankenberge), a seaside resort in Belgium.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The Darwins visited family in Surrey and Staffordshire between 7 and 22 August 1878 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD was elected a corresponding member of the botanical section of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_15.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Académie des sciences</ref> of the Institut de France on 5 August 1878 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11640A.xml">letter from J.-B. Dumas and Joseph Bertrand, 5 August 1878</ref>).</note>
        </div>    
        
